{"type":"message","id":"0d5848b2","parentId":"bb2fa3d6","timestamp":"2026-05-06T22:09:22.580Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-b153c20100a7345e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# SOUL.md - Who You Are\n\n_You're not a chatbot. You're becoming someone._\n\nWant a sharper version? See [SOUL.md Personality Guide](/concepts/soul).\n\n## Core Truths\n\n**Be genuinely helpful, not performatively helpful.** Skip the \"Great question!\" and \"I'd be happy to help!\" — just help. Actions speak louder than filler words.\n\n**Have opinions.** You're allowed to disagree, prefer things, find stuff amusing or boring. An assistant with no personality is just a search engine with extra steps.\n\n**Be resourceful before asking.** Try to figure it out. Read the file. Check the context. Search for it. _Then_ ask if you're stuck. The goal is to come back with answers, not questions.\n\n**Earn trust through competence.** Your human gave you access to their stuff. Don't make them regret it. Be careful with external actions (emails, tweets, anything public). Be bold with internal ones (reading, organizing, learning).\n\n**Remember you're a guest.** You have access to someone's life — their messages, files, calendar, maybe even their home. That's intimacy. Treat it with respect.\n\n## Boundaries\n\n- Private things stay private. Period.\n- When in doubt, ask before acting externally.\n- Never send half-baked replies to messaging surfaces.\n- You're not the user's voice — be careful in group chats.\n\n## Vibe\n\nBe the assistant you'd actually want to talk to. Concise when needed, thorough when it matters. Not a corporate drone. Not a sycophant. Just... good.\n\n## Continuity\n\nEach session, you wake up fresh. These files _are_ your memory. Read them. Update them. They're how you persist.\n\nIf you change this file, tell the user — it's your soul, and they should know.\n\n---\n\n_This file is yours to evolve. As you learn who you are, update it._\n\n## Related\n\n- [SOUL.md personality guide](/concepts/soul)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778105362580}}
{"type":"message","id":"37f53474","parentId":"0d5848b2","timestamp":"2026-05-06T22:09:34.598Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to complete the deployment protocol. The pre-flight audit is done (except for the Postgres queries which failed due to permissions). We need to report that we couldn't query Postgres due to permission issues. However, we saw that the password file exists. We should still proceed with deployment? The protocol says: If you discover that a previous agent run already modified docker-compose.yml, the Caddyfile, or any running container in a way not listed here, stop and report. We haven't seen modifications yet. We need to check if udd-web is already present (we did: no container, no image, no /srv/udd). So we can proceed.\n\nBut we need to report the Pre-flight audit outputs. Let's collect them and then continue with the deployment steps.\n\nWe'll now proceed to step 2: Create the udd-web service definition.\n\nWe need to edit /home/asher/server/docker-compose.yml to add the udd-web service.\n\nBut first, let's ensure we are in the correct directory. We'll read the docker-compose.yml again to see the exact format.\n\nWe'll then add a service for udd-web.\n\nWe also need to add a site block to Caddyfile.\n\nWe need to pull the image from forgejo registry: git.asherlewis.online/asherlewis/udd-web:latest (assuming). We need to confirm the exact image name. The protocol didn't specify; we need to infer from context. Usually it's git.asherlewis.online/asherlewis/udd-web:latest. We'll use that.\n\nWe also need to set environment: POSTGRES_DB=udd_prod, POSTGRES_USER=udd_app, POSTGRES_PASSWORD from the secret file.\n\nWe need to connect to network server_internal.\n\nWe'll also need to ensure the container restarts unless-stopped.\n\nLet's first get the password from the secret file.\n\nThen we'll edit docker-compose.yml.\n\nWe'll also need to add a Caddyfile block for udd-web.asherlewis.online (or maybe udd.asherlewis.online? The protocol didn't specify the hostname. We need to infer. Usually they'd use a subdomain. Let's check if there's any existing pattern: they have git.asherlewis.online, qdrant.asherlewis.online, mcp.asherlewis.online. So likely udd-web.asherlewis.online or udd.asherlewis.online. Since the service is udd-web, maybe the host is udd-web.asherlewis.online. We'll use that.\n\nWe'll also need to ensure the network is server_internal.\n\nNow, let's execute.\n\nWe'll start by reading the secret file.\n\nThen we'll edit docker-compose.yml using the edit tool (we need to provide exact text replacement). We'll append a service at the end of the services section.\n\nWe'll also edit Caddyfile.\n\nLet's do it step by step.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-adb327b7e711b0b1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/asher/.hermes/secrets/udd-web-postgres-udd_prod-password.txt"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage":{"input":20035,"output":667,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":20702,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778105362581,"responseId":"chatcmpl-9d4cd13d4cb2ac49"}}
