{"type":"message","id":"3932e831","parentId":"f564b66f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:15:21.731Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to fix the Caddyfile syntax. In Caddy v2, the directive is `header` not `header_up`. However, within a reverse_proxy subdirective, you can use `header_up` to set headers for the upstream request. Let's check Caddy docs: In reverse_proxy, you can use `header_up` to set headers sent to the upstream. So the syntax is:\n\nreverse_proxy <upstream> {\n    header_up <header> <value>\n}\n\nThus our block is correct: \n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n\nBut Caddy is complaining about unrecognized directive: header_up. Perhaps we need to place the header_up inside the reverse_proxy block but without the extra braces? Actually the syntax is:\n\nreverse_proxy [<match>] <upstream> {\n    header_up <header> <value>\n}\n\nSo we have:\n\nreverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n\nThat should be valid. Maybe the issue is that we need to put the header_up line directly under reverse_proxy without extra indentation? Let's check the existing Caddyfile for examples. There are none. Let's look at the Caddy documentation quickly via exec? We can try to test with caddy validate.\n\nBut we can also try a different approach: use the `header` directive inside the site block to set headers for the response, but we need to set X-Forwarded-Proto for the upstream. Actually the `header_up` is correct.\n\nLet's validate the Caddyfile:\n\ndocker exec caddy caddy validate --config /etc/caddy/Caddyfile --adapter caddyfile\n\nLet's do that.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-b9299d1975e81e39","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker exec caddy caddy validate --config /etc/caddy/Caddyfile --adapter caddyfile"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-s