       +\n           |         |          |                 |            |            |            |           | hermes=CTc/hermes\n udd_prod  | udd_app | UTF8     | libc            | en_US.utf8 | en_US.utf8 |            |           | \n(5 rows)\n\n\n=== 1.8 udd_prod and udd_app already exist? (from Phase 0) ===\n rolname \n---------\n udd_app\n(1 row)\n\n datname  \n----------\n udd_prod\n(1 row)\n\n\n=== 1.9 Check for any prior udd-web artifacts ===\nCONTAINER ID   IMAGE     COMMAND   CREATED   STATUS    PORTS     NAMES\nMISSING: /srv/udd\nWARNING: This output is designed for human readability. For machine-readable output, please use --format.\nno udd-web image\n\n=== 1.10 Forgejo registry reachability ===\nerror: cannot perform an interactive login from a non-TTY device\n\n=== 1.11 Confirm forgejo is using host port 3000 (collision check) ===\n3000/tcp -> 127.0.0.1:3000\n\n=== 1.12 Check if udd_app password file exists from Phase 0 ===\n-rw------- 1 asher asher 49 May  4 01:41 /home/asher/.hermes/secrets/udd-web-postgres-udd_prod-password.txt\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778117859370}}
{"type":"message","id":"f5b5aed1","parentId":"87f0d755","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:38:02.729Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We are at the point where we have the pre-flight audit completed. Now we need to proceed with the deployment steps from PART 2.\n\nWe have already done:\n  - Step 7.1: Verified no existing udd block in Caddyfile (it was clean).\n  - We need to do step 7.2: Append the site block to Caddyfile.\n  - Step 7.3: Reload Caddy.\n  - Step 7.4: Verify reload succeeded.\n\nBut note: We already attempted to append a udd block and had issues with the header_up directive. We fixed it to use `header_up` (which is correct for Caddy v2) but then got an error about unrecognized directive? Actually, the error said \"unrecognized directive: header_up\". However, in Caddy v2, `header_up` is a subdirective of `reverse_proxy`. So we must put it inside the `reverse_proxy` block.\n\nLet's look at the correct syntax from the protocol:\n\n```\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000\n\n    header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n}\n```\n\nWait, the protocol shows `header_up` at the same level as `reverse_proxy`? Actually, in the protocol it is shown as:\n\n```\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000\n\n    header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n}\n```\n\nBut in Caddy, the `header_up` directive is only allowed inside `reverse_proxy` (and a few other directives). So the correct way is to put it inside the `reverse_proxy` block.\n\nHowever, the protocol example might be mistaken. Let me check the Caddy documentation: \nActually, in Caddy v2, the `header_up` is a subdirective of `reverse_proxy`. So it must be indented under `reverse_proxy`.\n\nBut the protocol example shows it at the same level as `reverse_proxy` (i.e., under the site block). That would be an error.\n\nWe have two options:\n  1. Follow the protocol exactly as written (even if it's wrong) and see if it fails.\n  2. Use the correct syntax and hope that the protocol's intent was correct.\n\nGiven that the protocol says \"Append one site block; do not touch any existing blocks.\" and then gives the example, we should follow the example exactly as written? But note: the protocol is the source of truth for the task.\n\nHowever, we already tried the exact example and got an error about `header_up` being unrecognized. So we must adjust.\n\nLet me check the Caddy version: we saw v2.11.2. In Caddy v2, the `header_up` directive is only valid inside `reverse_proxy`, `fastcgi`, etc.\n\nTherefore, the correct way is to put `header_up` inside the `reverse_proxy` block.\n\nBut wait: the protocol example in the user's message might have been a copy-paste error? We are to execute the protocol exactly as written. However, if we do that, it will fail and we must report and stop? The golden rule says: if we discover that a previous agent run already modified ... in a way not listed here, stop and report. But this is not about a previous agent run, it's about the protocol itself being possibly incorrect.\n\nWe are to execute the protocol exactly as written. If it fails, we should stop and report? But note: the protocol is the instruction. We are to follow it. If it fails, we must report the failure.\n\nAlternatively, we can try to see if the protocol example is actually correct for a different version? But we are using Caddy v2.\n\nLet me try to validate the exact block from the protocol in a temporary file and see if Caddy accepts it.\n\nWe'll do that now.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-8921bb5eea9d3e04","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp && cat > test.caddy <<'EOF'\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000\n    header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n}\nEOF\ndocker run --rm -v $(pwd)/test.caddy:/etc/caddy/Caddyfile:ro caddy:2.11 caddy validate --config /etc/caddy/Caddyfile --adapter caddyfile 2>&1"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage":{"input":60811,"output":960,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61771,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778117859374,"responseId":"chatcmpl-a97a3408f60772bf"}}
