{"type":"message","id":"14c4dfe2","parentId":"ca058db0","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:38:41.826Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to fix the Caddyfile: header_up is not a valid directive in Caddy v2? Actually, header_up is a subdirective of reverse_proxy? Let's check: In Caddy 2, to set headers for reverse_proxy you use `header_up` inside the reverse_proxy block? Actually, the `header_up` directive is used to set request headers. It is a subdirective of `reverse_proxy`? Let's check quickly by running a test.\n\nBut from earlier test, we saw that `header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}` inside a reverse_proxy block produced a warning but was accepted. The error we got was \"unrecognized directive: header_up\" when placed directly inside the site block? Wait, we placed it inside the site block but outside reverse_proxy? Actually we had:\n\n```\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000\n    header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n}\n```\n\nThat is invalid because header_up is not a direct subdirective of the site block; it must be inside reverse_proxy? Actually, the documentation says header_up can be used in reverse_proxy, php_fastcgi, etc. So we need to put it inside the reverse_proxy block.\n\nLet's adjust: \n\n```\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWe tried that and got error \"unrecognized directive: header_up\" but maybe because of extra spaces? Actually we got that error when we had:\n\n```\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBut earlier test with test.caddy showed that header_up inside reverse_proxy block is valid (the warning said unnecessary but it was accepted). So why error? Possibly because we have a blank line? Let's check the exact content.\n\nWe'll rewrite the Caddyfile cleanly.\n\nLet's backup and then write the correct block.\n\nWe'll do:\n\n```\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBut note: the header_up directive may be unnecessary as Caddy already sets X-Forwarded-Proto by default? However, we'll follow the instruction.\n\nLet's first remove any existing udd block and then append the correct one.\n\nWe'll do:\n\n1. Remove any lines containing udd.asherlewis.online and its block.\n2. Append the correct block.\n\nWe can do with sed but easier to just rewrite the file: we have the original three blocks (git, qdrant, mcp). We'll keep them and add the udd block.\n\nLet's create a new Caddyfile with the four blocks.\n\nBut first, let's check if there are any other customizations we need to preserve. The existing file only had those three blocks. So we can safely recreate.\n\nLet's do:\n\n```\ncat > /home/asher/server/caddy/Caddyfile <<'EOF'\ngit.asherlewis.online {\n    reverse_proxy forgejo:3000\n}\n\nqdrant.asherlewis.online {\n    reverse_proxy qdrant:6333\n}\n\nmcp.asherlewis.online {\n    reverse_proxy localhost:8811\n}\n\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n}\nEOF\n```\n\nThen reload.\n\nLet's do that now.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-beea187fb9e62092","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat > /home/asher/server/caddy/Caddyfile <<'EOF'\ngit.asherlewis.online {\n    reverse_proxy forgejo:3000\n}\n\nqdrant.asherlewis.online {\n    reverse_proxy qdrant:6333\n}\n\nmcp.asherlewis.online {\n    reverse_proxy localhost:8811\n}\n\nudd.asherlewis.online {\n    encode zstd gzip\n    reverse_proxy udd-web:3000 {\n        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}\n    }\n}\nEOF"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage